<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,799,2043]" pageId="6" pageNumber="591">
In light of the information unearthed thus far, it is worth briefly investigating 
<taxonomicName authority="Joicey &amp; Talbot, 1918" authorityName="Joicey &amp; Talbot" authorityYear="1918" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="illyris" subSpecies="hamatus">
<emphasis box="[1060,1323,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="591">Papilio illyris hamatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Joicey, J. J. &amp; Talbot, G." pageId="6" pageNumber="591" pagination="271 - 272" refId="ref8389" refString="Joicey, J. J. &amp; Talbot, G. (1918) New Butterflies from Africa and the East. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 271 - 272. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1917. tb 02067. x" type="book chapter" year="1918">Joicey &amp; Talbot, 1918</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(now in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[509,624,835,861]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Graphium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[509,624,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="591">Graphium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), a species described from Suffert’s collection which has long remained a mystery. This taxon was described from a single male specimen and in the original description, the authors state the specimen originated from ‘ 
<collectingCountry box="[493,722,907,933]" name="Burundi" pageId="6" pageNumber="591">German East Africa</collectingCountry>
(British Occupation)’. This was discussed in detail by Smith &amp; Vane-Wright (2001) in their revision of the genus and without any further material available to them and slight differences in the wing-markings and genitalia, the name was retained as a ‘somewhat doubtful’ subspecies. 
<bibRefCitation author="Larsen, T. B." pageId="6" pageNumber="591" refId="ref8522" refString="Larsen, T. B. (2005) The Butterflies of West Africa. Apollo Books, Denmark, 2 vol., 900 pp." type="book" year="2005">Larsen (2005)</bibRefCitation>
postulated that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Joicey &amp; Talbot" authorityYear="1918" box="[412,559,1015,1041]" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="illyris" subSpecies="hamatus">
ssp. 
<emphasis box="[464,559,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="591">hamatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was likely to be conspecific with the Central African subspecies 
<emphasis box="[1317,1436,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="591">girardeaui</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Guilbot, R. &amp; Plantrou, J." box="[151,437,1051,1077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="591" pagination="68 - 73" refId="ref8220" refString="Guilbot, R. &amp; Plantrou, J. (1978) Note sur Graphium illyris (Hewitson) et revision systematique de l'espece [Lep. Papilionidae]. Bulletin de la Societe entomologique de France, 83 (3 - 4), 68 - 73." type="journal article" year="1978">Guilbot &amp; Plantrou, 1978</bibRefCitation>
and that the original vague locality was 
<emphasis box="[891,1021,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="591">patria falsa</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
